6368,-0.00164199,0.00261058,0.00326675,-0.00392136,-0.00852469,0.00064277,0.04469483,0.01450278,-0.03422742,0.01483978,-0.09400030,0.03533592,-0.06779319,0.00530125,-0.00009835,0.06748417,-0.04900962,-0.00661837,0.04019629,-0.02427364,-0.04547445,0.05077316,-0.02819009,0.00538538,-0.05914548,0.02365059,-0.04378951,0.04346906,-0.00304309,0.05650464,-0.02194131,0.01990933,0.02226314,-0.00307819,0.00059723,-0.03454694,-0.00846995,0.01301026,-0.04556758,0.03671246,0.01754043,0.05510363]',E'Prefork\n\nOn Linux, prefork typically relies on the `SO_REUSEPORT` socket option for kernel-assisted load distribution across workers. On Windows, Fiber falls back to `SO_REUSEADDR`; this is not a functional equivalent to Linux `SO_REUSEPORT` as it lacks native load balancing and may allow other processes to bind to the same port. Operators should validate this behavior against their security and availability requirements.\n\n##### Security Considerations','{"source": "go-fiber", "version": "3.3", "language": "go", "title": "Fiber", "section_title": "fiber", "url": "https://github.com/gofiber/fiber/blob/main/docs/api/fiber.md", "topics": "fiber,http,fiber", "categories": "web,go,rest"}');
